{{Infobox person |name = Mateusz Andrzej Mach |image = Mateusz Mach2.jpg |image_size = |birth_date = {{birth date and age|1997|4|15}} |birth_place = [[Gdańsk, Poland]] |death_date = |death_place = |resting_place = |resting_place_coordinates = |spouse = |children = |nationality = [[Polish people|Polish]] |other_names = |known_for = [[Five App, Opus]] |awards = [[Forbes 30 Under 30]], New Europe 100 List |education = [[New York University Abu Dhabi]]}}
'''Mateusz Mach''' (born April 15, 1997) is a Polish entrepreneur, start-up developer, founder of the world's first sign language messenger Five App<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.money.pl/gospodarka/tosieliczy/artykul/oto-18-letni-mateusz-mach-prezes-zarzadu,132,0,2009732.html|title=Oto 18-letni Mateusz Mach. Prezes zarządu firmy FiveApp wycenianej na ponad milion złotych|first=Sebastian|last=Ogórek|date=1 February 2016|publisher=}}</ref> and the co-founder of OPUS. Finalist of the ranking of the most influential European entrepreneurs under the age of thirty, [[Forbes 30 Under 30]].<ref name="forbes.com">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/mateusz-mach/#4a4a929b594f|title=Profile: Mateusz Mach|website=www.forbes.com}}</ref>
== Education == Mach graduated from high school [[III Liceum Ogólnokształcące im. Marynarki RP w Gdyni|III Liceum Ogólnokształcące im. Marynarki RP]] in [[Gdynia]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/teenager-polish-ceo-messenger-app-deaf-people-2016-1|title=This 18-year-old CEO in Poland is making the first sign language messaging app for deaf people|publisher=}}</ref> Poland with [[International Baccalaureate | International Baccalaureate Diploma]]. Currently he studies Economics at [[New York University Abu Dhabi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://businessinsider.com.pl/firmy/mateusz-mach-zaklada-platforme-muzyczna-opus/8gfjqeg|title=19-letni Polak podbija świat z nowym projektem. W dwa dni zebrał już 500 tys. zł|date=17 July 2017|publisher=}}</ref> He also attended courses at [[New York University Stern School of Business|New York University Leonard N. Stern School of Business]].{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}
== Career == In 2015, at the age of 17 Mateusz Mach debuted as an [[Entrepreneurship|entrepreneur]] when he introduced the Five App [[start-up]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/polish-entrepreneur-made-apple-watch-easier-for-deaf-people-2015-5|title=How a 17-year-old entrepreneur in Poland accidentally made the Apple Watch easier for deaf people|publisher=}}</ref> valued at two million [[Polish Zloty]].<ref>https://www.forbes.pl/pierwszy-milion/mateusz-mach-i-aplikacja-five-app-warta-miliony/7eegj89</ref> The mobile application was the world's first [[sign language]] messenger,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://impactcee.com/2016/10/13/five-app-is-the-worlds-first-sign-language-messenger/|title=Five App is the world’s first sign language messenger - ImpactCEE|date=13 October 2016|publisher=}}</ref> enabling [[deaf culture|deaf people]] to communicate efficiently using Android- and iOS-based devices. As a social impact project, the Five App was largely acclaimed among the targeted audience and acquired over ten thousands of users.<ref>https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=pl.essentialapps.five</ref> In 2017, Mach cofounded a new start-up, OPUS. The firm aims at the decentralization of [[music industry]] by introducing [[Ethereum]]-backed utility tokens for users to purchase access to music streaming services. He launched the [[Initial coin offering|Initial Coin Offering]] (ICO) of OPUS in the Summer of 2017.
== Achievements == In 2017 Mach was ranked in the European edition of the [[Forbes 30 Under 30]] Ranking,<ref name="forbes.com"/> thanks to the success of Five App. Mateusz Mach is also the finalist of New Europe 100 List, a project founded by [[Google]] and [[Financial Times]] in order to distinguish the most innovative entrepreneurs in the [[Central and Eastern Europe|region of Central and Eastern Europe]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/ece06f66-90a7-11e6-a72e-b428cb934b78|title=New Europe 100 — changemakers in central and eastern Europe|first=Henry|last=Foy|date=15 November 2016|website=Financial Times}}</ref>
